{"author":{"id":"138b13306404778af60b1d60d606624fec41556ddac480b2d5f762806ce84fed"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1782958624,"nonce":"Gxusu22/CzbSRkfo1rpttWVREks=","kind":"spec","title":"kref local-file tracking — B2: reconcile (file → entry) — design","content_type":"text/markdown"},{"type":3,"timestamp":1782958624,"nonce":"b7QBXyuw8hwz1aBpI+YrTYifnlg=","body":"# kref local-file tracking — B2: reconcile (file → entry) — design\n\n**Date:** 2026-06-26\n**Status:** IMPLEMENTED on `main` (commits `1f2fc62` engine, `fd753aa` CLI).\nOne change from the draft: B2 is strict pull-only — the §3.2 trailer \"re-stamp\"\nwas dropped (it would write the file); a trailer-less file still reconciles\n(entry-driven) and the missing trailer is reported, not repaired.\n**Scope:** `kref reconcile` — pull changes from tracked files into their entries.\nPull-only: it reads files and updates entries; it never writes or creates files.\nBuilds on B1 (tracking state + `TrackedPath`) and the existing idempotent\n`bridge.Ingest`. Write-back (entry → file) is B4; drift surfacing in\n`list`/`show` is B3.\n\n## 1. Context\n\nB1 gives each tracked entry a repo-relative `TrackedPath` and the `kref-id`\ntrailer binds file→entry. `bridge.Ingest` is already idempotent (unchanged file\n= no-op, changed file = update via the trailer). B2 adds the command that keeps\ntracked entries current with their on-disk files, on demand, without the\npost-commit hook and for files anywhere in the repo (including `.kref/`\nfloaters).\n\nDecided in brainstorming:\n- **Pull-only.** reconcile updates entries from files; it never writes/creates\n  files. \"Pushing entries onto the filesystem\" is B4 and explicitly excluded.\n- **Absent file ⇒ never materialize.** A tracked entry whose file is gone is not\n  recreated.\n- **Sweep-all by default, with a confirm prompt; single-target too.**\n\n## 2. Goals / non-goals\n\n**Goals**\n- `kref reconcile` sweeps every tracked entry whose file is present (or\n  relocatable, see §3.3), updating entries from changed files; idempotent.\n- `kref reconcile \u003cid|path\u003e` reconciles one entry, no prompt.\n- A blocking confirm prompt guards the bulk sweep (`-y`/`--yes` skips it).\n- Secrets fail closed by default; `--force` overrides with a loud warning.\n- Moved files self-heal: a tracked entry whose file moved is re-pointed.\n\n**Non-goals**\n- No write-back (entry → file) — B4.\n- No drift display in `list`/`show` — B3.\n- No new tracking semantics beyond re-pointing `TrackedPath` on a detected move.\n\n## 3. Design\n\n### 3.1 Command surface\n\n- `kref reconcile [-y|--yes] [--force]` — sweep all tracked entries. Before\n  applying, print the count of tracked files to be reconciled and a confirm\n  prompt (\"Proceed? [type yes]\") to stderr; `-y`/`--yes` skips it.\n- `kref reconcile \u003cid|path\u003e [--force]` — reconcile a single tracked entry\n  (resolved via `resolveArg`); no prompt.\n- `--json` emits the results array (like `ingest`).\n\nFlags:\n- `-y, --yes` — skip the bulk confirm prompt (no effect on single-target).\n- `--force` — override the fail-closed secret guard (§3.2). Distinct from\n  `-y`: two different safety gates.\n\n### 3.2 Per-entry behavior (entry-driven, never writes files)\n\nFor each selected tracked entry `E` with `TrackedPath` `P`:\n\n1. `P` missing → attempt self-heal (§3.3); if unresolved, result `missing`.\n2. `P` exists → read it, **secret-scan** (`scan.Scan`):\n   - findings and **not** `--force` → result `error` (fail closed): refuse to\n     pull a secret into `E` (which may live in a syncable tier). Mirrors the\n     existing ingest D3 guard.\n   - findings and `--force` → proceed, after a loud stderr warning naming the\n     finding and `E`'s tier (so a `shared`-tier force is unmissable).\n   - no findings → proceed.\n3. Strip any trailer (`bridge.SplitMarker`) to get the body; derive the title\n   (`titleFromMarkdown`). If the body or title differs from `E`, append the\n   update (`Store.Update`) — old bodies stay recoverable via `kref diff`. Record\n   a `reconcile` provenance event.\n4. Unchanged → result `unchanged` (idempotent).\n\nreconcile **never writes the file** (strict pull-only). If `P` lost its\n`kref-id` trailer, reconcile still updates the right entry (it is entry-driven)\nand the result flags the missing trailer; it does **not** re-stamp it — writing\nto the file is B4 (write-back) territory.\n\n**Entry-driven, not trailer-driven (key distinction).** `Ingest` discovers the\nentry from the file's trailer; reconcile already knows `E` from the tracking\nrecord. So reconcile updates `E` by id and never relies on the file's trailer to\nidentify it — a file that lost its trailer updates the right entry (and is\nre-stamped, step 4) instead of spawning a duplicate. This is why reconcile is\nnot simply `Ingest` in a loop.\n\n### 3.3 Self-heal moved files\n\nWhen `P` is missing, build (once per run, lazily — only if any tracked file is\nmissing) a **repo-wide trailer index**: walk `.md` files (including `.kref/`,\nskipping `.git`), read each trailer, map entry-id → [repo-relative paths].\n\nFor the missing entry `E`:\n- index has exactly one path for `E` → **`relocated`**: re-point\n  `Store.Track(E, newPath)` and reconcile from `newPath` (§3.2).\n- index has multiple paths for `E` (file copied) → **`ambiguous`**: report,\n  skip — do not guess.\n- index has none → **`missing`**: truly deleted.\n\n### 3.4 Output\n\nPer-entry result with an `Action` of `synced | unchanged | relocated | missing\n| ambiguous | error` plus the id, path, and any error string — modeled on\n`bridge.IngestResult`. Human mode prints a summary table; `--json` emits the\narray. A run with any `error` result exits non-zero (like `ingest`).\n\n## 4. Implementation slices (TDD)\n\n1. **Entry-driven reconcile of one entry** (`bridge`/`store`): read `TrackedPath`,\n   secret-scan (+`force` param), update the known entry, re-stamp a missing\n   trailer, `reconcile` provenance; idempotent. Unit-tested in `internal/bridge`.\n2. **Self-heal index + relocation**: trailer-index builder; missing → relocate /\n   ambiguous / missing classification; re-point `TrackedPath`.\n3. **CLI `kref reconcile`**: selection (all vs `\u003cid|path\u003e`), confirm prompt +\n   `-y`, `--force`, `--json`, summary; registered in `main.go`; `cli_test`.\n\n## 5. Testing\n\n- `internal/bridge`: changed tracked file → entry updated; unchanged → no-op;\n  trailer-less tracked file → right entry updated + re-stamped; secret →\n  `error` without `--force`, applied with `--force`; provenance records\n  `reconcile`.\n- Self-heal: moved file → `relocated` + `TrackedPath` re-pointed; copied (two\n  paths) → `ambiguous`; deleted → `missing`.\n- `cmd/kref`: bulk prompt blocks then proceeds on \"yes\"; `-y` skips; single\n  target skips prompt; `--json` shape; `--force` warning to stderr; non-zero\n  exit on an `error` result.\n\n## 6. Risks \u0026 mitigations\n\n- **`--force` breadth on a bulk sweep** overrides every secret hit at once. The\n  warning names each finding's tier; the safe habit (documented in help) is\n  `kref reconcile \u003cpath\u003e --force`. Not blocked, but loud.\n- **Trailer-index scan cost** — bounded (one `.md` walk), and lazy (only when a\n  missing path exists). Reuses the ingest walk's skip rules (`.git`, and it\n  *includes* `.kref/`).\n- **Ambiguous trailers** (a file copied, two paths) — never auto-resolved;\n  reported so the user fixes it.\n\n## 7. Out of scope\n\n- **B4** write-back (entry → file) with a `git merge-file` conflict model.\n- **B3** drift detection / `list`/`show` surfacing."}]}